Classes allow you to store information.

1. You start with a function
function Counter (){
    return (
        <div>
        <h1>Hello World</h1>
        </div>
    );
}

2. rename top line like so and move your function into it.

class Counter extends React.Component{
    function () {
        return (
        <div>
        <h1>Hello World</h1>
        </div>
    );
    }
};

3. rename function to render

class Counter extends React.Component{
    render () {
        return (
        <div>
        <h1>Hello World</h1>
        </div>
    );
    }
};

4. Setting a class to have its own variables, 

class Counter extends React.Component{
    constructor(props) {
        super(props);
    }
    render () {
        let value = 1;
        return (
        <div>
        <h1>{value}</h1>
        </div>
    );
    }
};

5. Accessing the variables, when someone clicks on the counter, it increases by 1

class Counter extends React.Component{
    constructor(props) {
        super(props);
        this.state = {
            value: 1
        };
    }
    render () {
        return (
        <div>
        <h1 onClick = {() => {
            this.setState({
                value: this.state.value + 1
            })
        }}>{this.state.value}</h1>
        </div>)
    }
};

export default Counter;